WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.964 align:middle line:90%


00:00:08.964 --> 00:00:12.450 align:middle line:10%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:12.450 --> 00:00:18.912 align:middle line:90%


00:00:18.912 --> 00:00:20.370 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY SMITH:
Welcome to the show.

00:00:20.370 --> 00:00:21.200 align:middle line:90%
I'm Emery Smith.

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:23.150 align:middle line:10%
I'm here again with David Adair.

00:00:23.150 --> 00:00:24.450 align:middle line:10%
David, welcome to the show.

00:00:24.450 --> 00:00:25.310 align:middle line:10%
>>DAVID ADAIR: Thank
you for having me.

00:00:25.310 --> 00:00:27.810 align:middle line:10%
>>EMERY: One of the things that
crossed my mind all the time

00:00:27.810 --> 00:00:30.080 align:middle line:10%
is meeting someone like
you that has actually

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:32.390 align:middle line:10%
had hands-on experience
in-- we call them

00:00:32.390 --> 00:00:34.820 align:middle line:10%
ARVs, alien
reproduction vehicles.

00:00:34.820 --> 00:00:36.980 align:middle line:84%
If we have an
extraterrestrial vehicle,

00:00:36.980 --> 00:00:39.590 align:middle line:84%
we will try to 3D
print these things.

00:00:39.590 --> 00:00:43.460 align:middle line:84%
We will scan them before even
touching them to make sure

00:00:43.460 --> 00:00:45.710 align:middle line:84%
that there's nothing
too harmful in there

00:00:45.710 --> 00:00:47.960 align:middle line:84%
or whether or not we should
open the device up or not.

00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:52.290 align:middle line:84%
You actually hand-carved,
from what I've heard--

00:00:52.290 --> 00:00:53.090 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:00:53.090 --> 00:00:54.170 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: --a vehicle.

00:00:54.170 --> 00:00:55.385 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:00:55.385 --> 00:00:56.185 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

00:00:56.185 --> 00:01:00.470 align:middle line:84%
I find all this funny because
you call it alien reproduction

00:01:00.470 --> 00:01:02.480 align:middle line:90%
vehicles, ARV.

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:04.910 align:middle line:10%
God, I've done this
all my life and I never

00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:08.690 align:middle line:10%
thought it had a name like that.

00:01:08.690 --> 00:01:12.050 align:middle line:10%
My mother was a master
modeler, and so I learned

00:01:12.050 --> 00:01:14.270 align:middle line:10%
building models from her.

00:01:14.270 --> 00:01:16.280 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not talking
about model kits.

00:01:16.280 --> 00:01:22.490 align:middle line:84%
I'm talking about dragging out
a 100 or 500-pound block of clay

00:01:22.490 --> 00:01:23.990 align:middle line:90%
and go to work on things.

00:01:23.990 --> 00:01:27.920 align:middle line:90%
That's how I built Pitholem.

00:01:27.920 --> 00:01:32.430 align:middle line:84%
I couldn't find a standard
off-the-shelf rocket body.

00:01:32.430 --> 00:01:36.120 align:middle line:84%
Everything was way
too weak, flimsy.

00:01:36.120 --> 00:01:39.405 align:middle line:84%
It'd be like trying to use
balsa wood against a battleship.

00:01:39.405 --> 00:01:40.620 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Right.

00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:43.770 align:middle line:10%
>>ADAIR: It's just a crazy
story the way it developed.

00:01:43.770 --> 00:01:46.450 align:middle line:10%
Art Bell was the first
to ask me about it.

00:01:46.450 --> 00:01:49.800 align:middle line:10%
And I came out and I said,
yeah, I built Pitholem

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:53.660 align:middle line:10%
out of this raw material
that General LeMay had

00:01:53.660 --> 00:01:58.140 align:middle line:10%
to go find because, I said, the
rockets aren't going to work.

00:01:58.140 --> 00:01:59.220 align:middle line:10%
We built the engine.

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:03.430 align:middle line:10%
Now we've got to build the
rocket around the engine.

00:02:03.430 --> 00:02:05.230 align:middle line:84%
And LeMay actually
liked that approach.

00:02:05.230 --> 00:02:07.820 align:middle line:84%
He said, that makes
sense actually.

00:02:07.820 --> 00:02:10.160 align:middle line:84%
But I told him, I need
different materials.

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:11.690 align:middle line:90%
He goes, what kind of materials?

00:02:11.690 --> 00:02:15.020 align:middle line:10%
Raw materials, stuff
that doesn't exist.

00:02:15.020 --> 00:02:21.560 align:middle line:10%
I said, I need something
extremely hard, take high heat,

00:02:21.560 --> 00:02:23.040 align:middle line:10%
and it can be heavy.

00:02:23.040 --> 00:02:26.687 align:middle line:10%
The heavier it is, the better
it is because, normally, that's

00:02:26.687 --> 00:02:28.020 align:middle line:10%
the opposite of a normal rocket.

00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:28.510 align:middle line:10%
>>EMERY: Right.

00:02:28.510 --> 00:02:30.990 align:middle line:10%
>>ADAIR: You're trying to
make thin walls, less weight,

00:02:30.990 --> 00:02:31.970 align:middle line:10%
move fast.

00:02:31.970 --> 00:02:33.750 align:middle line:90%
No, I had the problem.

00:02:33.750 --> 00:02:35.850 align:middle line:84%
I had a power curve
I was dealing with.

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:37.640 align:middle line:84%
And that power curve
was telling me,

00:02:37.640 --> 00:02:40.520 align:middle line:84%
you know, this thing
can launch a building,

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:43.180 align:middle line:84%
so I've got to have
something heavy.

00:02:43.180 --> 00:02:45.990 align:middle line:10%
So LeMay, gone for a few days.

00:02:45.990 --> 00:02:49.820 align:middle line:10%
Comes back, and he
tells me, I think

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:52.160 align:middle line:10%
I've found a material
that would work.

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:54.470 align:middle line:10%
We've got six tons of it.

00:02:54.470 --> 00:02:58.280 align:middle line:10%
Six tons, that should be enough.

00:02:58.280 --> 00:03:00.680 align:middle line:90%
How much volume is six tons?

00:03:00.680 --> 00:03:02.790 align:middle line:84%
Because six tons of
aluminum would fill a room.

00:03:02.790 --> 00:03:03.590 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Right.

00:03:03.590 --> 00:03:04.390 align:middle line:90%
That's a lot.

00:03:04.390 --> 00:03:07.000 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Six tons of lead would
just be the size of a desk.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:08.270 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Right.

00:03:08.270 --> 00:03:10.640 align:middle line:10%
>>ADAIR: And he said, you
do think about this stuff,

00:03:10.640 --> 00:03:11.440 align:middle line:10%
don't you?

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:12.970 align:middle line:90%
I said, yeah, I have to.

00:03:12.970 --> 00:03:18.512 align:middle line:84%
So he said, this is really
heavy and really dense.

00:03:18.512 --> 00:03:19.970 align:middle line:10%
I said, well, where
did you get it?

00:03:19.970 --> 00:03:23.120 align:middle line:10%
He goes, England.

00:03:23.120 --> 00:03:25.175 align:middle line:10%
I said, yeah, what company?

00:03:25.175 --> 00:03:28.100 align:middle line:10%
He said, you know,
you can't know.

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:30.390 align:middle line:90%
I can't tell you.

00:03:30.390 --> 00:03:32.980 align:middle line:90%
What's the origin of it?

00:03:32.980 --> 00:03:34.900 align:middle line:84%
As far as you need
to know, unknown.

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:35.700 align:middle line:90%
Who is they?

00:03:35.700 --> 00:03:36.270 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Yeah, who?

00:03:36.270 --> 00:03:37.620 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: And he goes, people.

00:03:37.620 --> 00:03:38.420 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Oh.

00:03:38.420 --> 00:03:39.220 align:middle line:90%
OK, I know that.

00:03:39.220 --> 00:03:40.070 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: You know.

00:03:40.070 --> 00:03:41.550 align:middle line:90%
I said, people, OK.

00:03:41.550 --> 00:03:44.790 align:middle line:10%
Well did them people
have any spec sheets?

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:45.685 align:middle line:10%
No.

00:03:45.685 --> 00:03:47.430 align:middle line:10%
I went, oh, God.

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:49.958 align:middle line:10%
So the material comes in.

00:03:49.958 --> 00:03:51.375 align:middle line:10%
We sit it down on
the floor and, I

00:03:51.375 --> 00:03:54.950 align:middle line:10%
mean, we're using
big forklift, Hyster.

00:03:54.950 --> 00:03:58.600 align:middle line:84%
Set it down, and it's heavy
because I can hear the floor--

00:03:58.600 --> 00:03:59.400 align:middle line:90%
[IMITATES CREAKING]

00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:00.832 align:middle line:90%
--you know, taking the weight.

00:04:00.832 --> 00:04:02.040 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: What's it look like?

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:02.840 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Oh, man.

00:04:02.840 --> 00:04:04.960 align:middle line:90%
It's square.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:07.170 align:middle line:90%
It's a big block.

00:04:07.170 --> 00:04:09.990 align:middle line:84%
And we get the
packing off of it.

00:04:09.990 --> 00:04:12.480 align:middle line:84%
And normally, when something
like that would come in,

00:04:12.480 --> 00:04:13.688 align:middle line:90%
I'd try to unpack it myself--

00:04:13.688 --> 00:04:14.488 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Mm-hm.

00:04:14.488 --> 00:04:15.739 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: And I dig for labels.

00:04:15.739 --> 00:04:16.539 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Right.

00:04:16.539 --> 00:04:18.709 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Because they take
all the labels off of it.

00:04:18.709 --> 00:04:20.209 align:middle line:84%
But every once in
a while, you know,

00:04:20.209 --> 00:04:24.770 align:middle line:84%
I've been inspected by number
D. Well, I find something.

00:04:24.770 --> 00:04:27.470 align:middle line:84%
So I knew it came from
England, but a tiny little tag

00:04:27.470 --> 00:04:32.060 align:middle line:84%
down there said S.H.A.P.E.
with a dot after each letter.

00:04:32.060 --> 00:04:37.620 align:middle line:10%
And thanks to Bob Dean, I knew
what that was years later.

00:04:37.620 --> 00:04:40.520 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know at the time I was
looking at it, but S.H.A.P.E.

00:04:40.520 --> 00:04:44.120 align:middle line:84%
is Supreme Headquarters
Allied Powers Europe.

00:04:44.120 --> 00:04:47.960 align:middle line:84%
And Bob Dean, that's
where he worked.

00:04:47.960 --> 00:04:50.330 align:middle line:10%
He worked with Colonel
Corso, and both of them

00:04:50.330 --> 00:04:53.625 align:middle line:10%
were charged with finding
all foreign technologies.

00:04:53.625 --> 00:04:55.250 align:middle line:84%
So I'm looking at
that, I remember back

00:04:55.250 --> 00:04:56.830 align:middle line:84%
when I found the
S.H.A.P.E. thing,

00:04:56.830 --> 00:04:59.847 align:middle line:84%
hid it because I didn't want
anyone to know I saw it,

00:04:59.847 --> 00:05:01.180 align:middle line:90%
and this thing is sitting there.

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:02.690 align:middle line:90%
It's a big block of--

00:05:02.690 --> 00:05:06.290 align:middle line:84%
the color of this stuff
is hard to describe.

00:05:06.290 --> 00:05:11.330 align:middle line:90%
It's iridescent.

00:05:11.330 --> 00:05:14.860 align:middle line:10%
And it would change colors
when lights hit it, you know,

00:05:14.860 --> 00:05:17.120 align:middle line:10%
like a rolling sheen.

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:19.520 align:middle line:84%
And that's the next
thing, the sheen of it.

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:23.315 align:middle line:84%
It looked like it
was wet, so shiny.

00:05:23.315 --> 00:05:24.770 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Was it radioactive?

00:05:24.770 --> 00:05:25.782 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: No.

00:05:25.782 --> 00:05:26.740 align:middle line:90%
That's a good question.

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:29.010 align:middle line:84%
First thing I do when
something like that comes in,

00:05:29.010 --> 00:05:29.690 align:middle line:90%
grab a Geiger counter.

00:05:29.690 --> 00:05:30.940 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Get a Geiger counter?

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:33.480 align:middle line:10%
>>ADAIR: So it was flat
on the Geiger counter,

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:37.702 align:middle line:10%
but every time I got near it, my
hair would stand straight out.

00:05:37.702 --> 00:05:41.100 align:middle line:84%
I'm going, man, the
static electricity.

00:05:41.100 --> 00:05:43.887 align:middle line:10%
So I just had a
compass in my desk,

00:05:43.887 --> 00:05:45.720 align:middle line:10%
and I thought, well,
let's see what happens.

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:49.320 align:middle line:84%
Get near it, man, the compass
just spun like a drill bit.

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:50.120 align:middle line:90%
You know--

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:50.920 align:middle line:90%
[IMITATES WHIRRING]

00:05:50.920 --> 00:05:53.040 align:middle line:10%
And I thought, God.

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:55.740 align:middle line:84%
So I wanted to see if
that sheen was all the way

00:05:55.740 --> 00:05:57.720 align:middle line:84%
through the metal, or
if we're going to be

00:05:57.720 --> 00:05:59.640 align:middle line:90%
dealing with some other color.

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:02.770 align:middle line:84%
So I grab a drill
bit and drill on it,

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:04.950 align:middle line:84%
and the drill just slides
all over the surface,

00:06:04.950 --> 00:06:07.065 align:middle line:84%
not making a single
scratch anywhere.

00:06:07.065 --> 00:06:08.220 align:middle line:90%
I said, fine.

00:06:08.220 --> 00:06:12.000 align:middle line:84%
I'll get a punch and get
a foothold on this thing.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:15.560 align:middle line:84%
So I grab a punch and
about a five-pound hammer.

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:16.360 align:middle line:90%
Ping!

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:18.890 align:middle line:84%
The punch went clear
to the ceiling.

00:06:18.890 --> 00:06:21.180 align:middle line:90%
Looked down, not a scratch.

00:06:21.180 --> 00:06:23.190 align:middle line:90%
So I can't do anything with it.

00:06:23.190 --> 00:06:24.690 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY: Well, how
can you shape it?

00:06:24.690 --> 00:06:27.430 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Well, that's
the next set of problems.

00:06:27.430 --> 00:06:31.320 align:middle line:10%
So LeMay comes in and
he says, how's it look?

00:06:31.320 --> 00:06:34.380 align:middle line:90%
I said, pretty, nice and shiny.

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:39.700 align:middle line:84%
I said, so damn hard I can't
even make a scratch on it.

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:40.930 align:middle line:90%
You got any spec sheets?

00:06:40.930 --> 00:06:41.950 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:43.840 align:middle line:90%
What's the flash point?

00:06:43.840 --> 00:06:47.020 align:middle line:84%
We're going to probably
have to cast this thing.

00:06:47.020 --> 00:06:48.000 align:middle line:90%
And he looked at me.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.470 align:middle line:90%
He said, casting?

00:06:50.470 --> 00:06:52.770 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, you're going
to have to cast this.

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:56.450 align:middle line:84%
He said, well, what's
the molds then?

00:06:56.450 --> 00:06:59.022 align:middle line:84%
And I thought, I'll
have to make them.

00:06:59.022 --> 00:06:59.980 align:middle line:90%
And he's looking at me.

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:03.260 align:middle line:84%
He goes, you can make
molds for this whole thing?

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:06.220 align:middle line:90%
I said, sure, it's modeling.

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:07.860 align:middle line:90%
So he said, what do you need?

00:07:07.860 --> 00:07:10.262 align:middle line:90%
500 pounds of modeling clay.

00:07:10.262 --> 00:07:11.220 align:middle line:90%
So they bring in this--

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:12.387 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: The next big chunk.

00:07:12.387 --> 00:07:14.863 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: The next forklift
comes in with a damn big block.

00:07:14.863 --> 00:07:16.030 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: That's a big block.

00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:18.590 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Oh, it was as
big as a sofa, a couch.

00:07:18.590 --> 00:07:19.390 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Right.

00:07:19.390 --> 00:07:20.950 align:middle line:84%
That's what we use
to make cars with.

00:07:20.950 --> 00:07:21.810 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:07:21.810 --> 00:07:23.470 align:middle line:84%
I look like a Ford
engineer over there.

00:07:23.470 --> 00:07:25.770 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY: I'm just thinking of
you and Lamborghini back there.

00:07:25.770 --> 00:07:26.430 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, exactly.

00:07:26.430 --> 00:07:27.760 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY: You know, shaving
off these edges of this craft.

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:29.135 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Well,
that's what I did.

00:07:29.135 --> 00:07:31.770 align:middle line:84%
I just rolled the thing out
in the middle of the room

00:07:31.770 --> 00:07:33.840 align:middle line:84%
and started doing my
measurements off the engine.

00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:36.810 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to have to build
the body around the engine.

00:07:36.810 --> 00:07:38.260 align:middle line:90%
It's no big deal.

00:07:38.260 --> 00:07:41.820 align:middle line:84%
You get all these clay tools,
your shapers, bends, spoons,

00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:42.690 align:middle line:90%
all this stuff.

00:07:42.690 --> 00:07:45.660 align:middle line:84%
And you start scraping and
scraping and modeling it

00:07:45.660 --> 00:07:49.830 align:middle line:84%
and look at it by eye and
just keep working on it.

00:07:49.830 --> 00:07:52.830 align:middle line:84%
Well, about a week
later, I finally

00:07:52.830 --> 00:07:59.200 align:middle line:84%
get the first mold section
done, and it fits perfectly

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:00.400 align:middle line:90%
with the engine.

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:01.518 align:middle line:90%
That's the front half.

00:08:01.518 --> 00:08:03.310 align:middle line:84%
Then there's a second
half on the backside.

00:08:03.310 --> 00:08:05.380 align:middle line:10%
The engine's right in
the middle of the rocket.

00:08:05.380 --> 00:08:06.180 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Mm-hm.

00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:07.976 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: The whole idea is to--

00:08:07.976 --> 00:08:10.690 align:middle line:84%
you know, it's very
simple physics.

00:08:10.690 --> 00:08:12.720 align:middle line:84%
You blow up a
balloon, let go of it.

00:08:12.720 --> 00:08:12.880 align:middle line:90%
You go--

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:13.740 align:middle line:90%
[IMITATES DEFLATING]

00:08:13.740 --> 00:08:15.040 align:middle line:90%
It takes off.

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:17.530 align:middle line:84%
As the air is pushing on the
end of the balloon and it's

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:24.130 align:middle line:84%
coming out the nozzle,
thrust, rocket or jet engine.

00:08:24.130 --> 00:08:26.090 align:middle line:90%
In this case, it's a rocket.

00:08:26.090 --> 00:08:29.560 align:middle line:84%
So what the air is pushing
on the end of the balloon

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:33.230 align:middle line:90%
we call a diffuser wall.

00:08:33.230 --> 00:08:35.997 align:middle line:84%
So I had to build the
first-- the diffuser wall.

00:08:35.997 --> 00:08:37.789 align:middle line:84%
That's what the engine
is going to push on.

00:08:37.789 --> 00:08:39.200 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY: This is
the Pitholem engine.

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:39.640 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Right.

00:08:39.640 --> 00:08:40.440 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: OK.

00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:44.600 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: So I had to build
a cradle for the engine

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:46.400 align:middle line:90%
to fit into.

00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:53.930 align:middle line:84%
And it cannot be, you know,
ribs or beams or brackets.

00:08:53.930 --> 00:08:59.120 align:middle line:84%
No, we're talking solid
metal, four feet thick.

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:02.257 align:middle line:84%
And people go, well, that thing
will never get off the ground.

00:09:02.257 --> 00:09:03.720 align:middle line:90%
Uh-uh.

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:06.098 align:middle line:84%
I'm working on a power
curve you've got to see.

00:09:06.098 --> 00:09:08.390 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY: And that's why you
need this special material?

00:09:08.390 --> 00:09:09.640 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:13.590 align:middle line:84%
I would've welded a safe on
it if it would've worked.

00:09:13.590 --> 00:09:17.320 align:middle line:84%
I just need tremendous
weight to slow it down.

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:20.490 align:middle line:84%
The problem is not going to be
not enough speed getting up.

00:09:20.490 --> 00:09:24.210 align:middle line:84%
It's trying to keep it contained
because this whole system isn't

00:09:24.210 --> 00:09:26.580 align:middle line:90%
made to be launched from Earth.

00:09:26.580 --> 00:09:29.340 align:middle line:84%
It's really designed to
be launched in space.

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:31.770 align:middle line:84%
But I'm going to have to
overcome the power curve

00:09:31.770 --> 00:09:35.470 align:middle line:84%
problem because that power curve
is going to launch an Empire

00:09:35.470 --> 00:09:37.570 align:middle line:90%
State Building.

00:09:37.570 --> 00:09:39.190 align:middle line:90%
So that's what I'm dealing with.

00:09:39.190 --> 00:09:42.520 align:middle line:84%
The ascension is going
to be so fast, that thing

00:09:42.520 --> 00:09:46.180 align:middle line:84%
is going to be red hot
going through the atmosphere

00:09:46.180 --> 00:09:49.240 align:middle line:84%
like they do when they
come in on a descent.

00:09:49.240 --> 00:09:50.040 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Right.

00:09:50.040 --> 00:09:52.100 align:middle line:10%
>>ADAIR: I'm going to have
the same problem going ascent.

00:09:52.100 --> 00:09:52.510 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Oh yeah.

00:09:52.510 --> 00:09:54.100 align:middle line:90%
That's how fast you're going.

00:09:54.100 --> 00:09:55.810 align:middle line:84%
So what speeds
are we looking at?

00:09:55.810 --> 00:09:58.320 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Eventually,
when we get to launch,

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:02.620 align:middle line:84%
I cover 125 miles
in 3.2 seconds.

00:10:02.620 --> 00:10:04.330 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: So you make this mold.

00:10:04.330 --> 00:10:06.790 align:middle line:90%
And now the next step is what?

00:10:06.790 --> 00:10:10.060 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Well, we sprayed
polyurethane onto the mold

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:12.070 align:middle line:90%
to make it hard.

00:10:12.070 --> 00:10:14.490 align:middle line:10%
And then we lifted
it out of there,

00:10:14.490 --> 00:10:17.440 align:middle line:10%
and all the Air Force
people lifted it out.

00:10:17.440 --> 00:10:19.300 align:middle line:10%
Then we would crate
it up, and we send it

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:23.580 align:middle line:10%
to some place LeMay had.

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:26.435 align:middle line:10%
And I said, man,
what kind of furnace

00:10:26.435 --> 00:10:27.810 align:middle line:10%
are you going to
melt this thing?

00:10:27.810 --> 00:10:29.700 align:middle line:10%
You won't tell me
the flash point.

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:34.660 align:middle line:10%
Either you know and you're not
telling me or you don't know.

00:10:34.660 --> 00:10:36.460 align:middle line:84%
I said, it's got
to be incredible.

00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:38.410 align:middle line:90%
I said, we need the sun.

00:10:38.410 --> 00:10:39.520 align:middle line:90%
And he looked at me.

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:43.000 align:middle line:84%
He said, well, how
perceptive of you?

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.360 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, we're using nuclear fire.

00:10:45.360 --> 00:10:47.080 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going, God
almighty, you're

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:50.800 align:middle line:84%
going to use a nuclear
furnace, wherever that is.

00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:54.550 align:middle line:10%
So anyway, we send
the casting off,

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:56.740 align:middle line:10%
and then I work on
the second parts

00:10:56.740 --> 00:10:58.960 align:middle line:10%
and some intermediate
parts, but I make

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:00.560 align:middle line:10%
casting parts for everything.

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:06.290 align:middle line:10%
Finally get it all
done, and I remember--

00:11:06.290 --> 00:11:08.350 align:middle line:10%
you know, we're doing
this in sections, right?

00:11:08.350 --> 00:11:11.550 align:middle line:84%
So the whole thing's
not been put together.

00:11:11.550 --> 00:11:15.170 align:middle line:84%
And LeMay was already
starting to-- he's keeping a--

00:11:15.170 --> 00:11:17.310 align:middle line:84%
it's like I'm
under a microscope.

00:11:17.310 --> 00:11:20.500 align:middle line:84%
But he's already seeing
what the overall look's

00:11:20.500 --> 00:11:22.240 align:middle line:90%
going to be when I'm done.

00:11:22.240 --> 00:11:25.390 align:middle line:90%
And he said, god almighty.

00:11:25.390 --> 00:11:28.500 align:middle line:84%
He goes, I've seen
some rockets in my day.

00:11:28.500 --> 00:11:31.480 align:middle line:84%
He said, that thing looks like
something from another world.

00:11:31.480 --> 00:11:34.670 align:middle line:90%
And I said, hmm.

00:11:34.670 --> 00:11:37.825 align:middle line:84%
More people were
right than you think.

00:11:37.825 --> 00:11:38.950 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: You were inspired.

00:11:38.950 --> 00:11:42.420 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: I guess so, and you're
channeling it, they call it.

00:11:42.420 --> 00:11:45.295 align:middle line:84%
But I got all the castings
done, sent them out,

00:11:45.295 --> 00:11:47.420 align:middle line:84%
and I've never told anybody
this part of the story.

00:11:47.420 --> 00:11:50.020 align:middle line:10%
Nobody's ever asked me.

00:11:50.020 --> 00:11:53.650 align:middle line:84%
The more you get down
to the nuts and bolts,

00:11:53.650 --> 00:11:57.220 align:middle line:84%
all this keeps rolling out
because, well, first of all,

00:11:57.220 --> 00:11:59.740 align:middle line:84%
you're making me
remember everything.

00:11:59.740 --> 00:12:05.850 align:middle line:84%
I remember clearly seeing myself
in the shop on that clay mold.

00:12:05.850 --> 00:12:09.530 align:middle line:84%
I looked like a mud
diver for a week.

00:12:09.530 --> 00:12:10.410 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHING]

00:12:10.410 --> 00:12:15.280 align:middle line:84%
And your feet would
stick to the floor.

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:18.040 align:middle line:84%
Air Force people came in and
scraped up a lot of stuff,

00:12:18.040 --> 00:12:19.000 align:middle line:90%
and they helped.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:19.800 align:middle line:90%
But anyway--

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:21.840 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY: They probably thought
you were just a slob back

00:12:21.840 --> 00:12:22.020 align:middle line:90%
there--

00:12:22.020 --> 00:12:23.960 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, well-- no,
they actually thought--

00:12:23.960 --> 00:12:25.140 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY: --covered
head to toe with this.

00:12:25.140 --> 00:12:25.710 align:middle line:90%
I can see you with this clay.

00:12:25.710 --> 00:12:27.168 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: They were
very supportive.

00:12:27.168 --> 00:12:28.950 align:middle line:84%
They just thought
this whole project--

00:12:28.950 --> 00:12:31.140 align:middle line:90%
some of them were experienced--

00:12:31.140 --> 00:12:32.437 align:middle line:90%
what you call black op people.

00:12:32.437 --> 00:12:33.270 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Sure, yeah.

00:12:33.270 --> 00:12:35.850 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: So God knows
what they've seen.

00:12:35.850 --> 00:12:39.520 align:middle line:84%
But they would come up
to me and go, damn, kid.

00:12:39.520 --> 00:12:43.150 align:middle line:84%
I know you're only 17, but
I've been at this for years.

00:12:43.150 --> 00:12:46.750 align:middle line:84%
I've seen stuff I can't
even begin to tell you.

00:12:46.750 --> 00:12:49.650 align:middle line:84%
But I want to tell you, you
are out there on the edge.

00:12:49.650 --> 00:12:52.910 align:middle line:84%
You are so far out there,
you're coming back.

00:12:52.910 --> 00:12:55.750 align:middle line:90%
And I went, whatever that means.

00:12:55.750 --> 00:12:58.930 align:middle line:84%
But he said, really
cool-looking stuff you're doing.

00:12:58.930 --> 00:13:02.990 align:middle line:84%
So we send everything
off, and LeMay tells me

00:13:02.990 --> 00:13:05.330 align:middle line:90%
about the material.

00:13:05.330 --> 00:13:06.200 align:middle line:90%
I'm begging.

00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:09.410 align:middle line:84%
You know, please,
God, for God's sake,

00:13:09.410 --> 00:13:12.350 align:middle line:84%
tell me something
what I'm working with.

00:13:12.350 --> 00:13:14.820 align:middle line:84%
And he gives me
the name, carbnite.

00:13:14.820 --> 00:13:18.860 align:middle line:84%
Now when I said that on
Art Bell back in '97,

00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:21.260 align:middle line:84%
all these experts
come flying at me.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:24.770 align:middle line:84%
He's a lying-- you know,
he don't know nothing.

00:13:24.770 --> 00:13:28.000 align:middle line:84%
That's what they froze Han
Solo in in "Star Wars."

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:29.690 align:middle line:90%
He's just copying it.

00:13:29.690 --> 00:13:30.680 align:middle line:90%
I'm from the South.

00:13:30.680 --> 00:13:33.292 align:middle line:10%
I approach English as
a second language, OK?

00:13:33.292 --> 00:13:35.750 align:middle line:84%
Come from the land where y'all
is singular and all y'all is

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:37.020 align:middle line:90%
plural.

00:13:37.020 --> 00:13:41.540 align:middle line:10%
So it's carbnite, not carbonite.

00:13:41.540 --> 00:13:45.890 align:middle line:84%
C-A-R-B-N-I-T-E, that's what
I'm working with, carbnite.

00:13:45.890 --> 00:13:49.140 align:middle line:84%
Carbonite is what you
froze Han Solo in.

00:13:49.140 --> 00:13:50.880 align:middle line:90%
Stuff's called carbnite.

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:53.970 align:middle line:84%
There's only six tons of it
in the world, and that's it.

00:13:53.970 --> 00:13:56.490 align:middle line:90%
Origin, unknown.

00:13:56.490 --> 00:13:59.760 align:middle line:90%
Other specs on it, unknown.

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:03.110 align:middle line:84%
And I don't know, it could
have been a crate that

00:14:03.110 --> 00:14:04.840 align:middle line:90%
fell off an alien cargo ship.

00:14:04.840 --> 00:14:05.640 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:14:05.640 --> 00:14:07.265 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY: It had to
come from somewhere.

00:14:07.265 --> 00:14:10.880 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, but, God, it was
nothing like I've ever seen.

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:13.420 align:middle line:84%
And I was wondering,
is the sheen still

00:14:13.420 --> 00:14:16.270 align:middle line:84%
going to be there after going
through a nuclear furnace?

00:14:16.270 --> 00:14:20.120 align:middle line:10%
You know, is it going to
be flat in color or what?

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:25.050 align:middle line:10%
Well, the first parts came
back and we opened them up.

00:14:25.050 --> 00:14:28.590 align:middle line:84%
And I swear to god,
the exact same sheen's

00:14:28.590 --> 00:14:33.822 align:middle line:84%
there, completely shaped
into the casting I made.

00:14:33.822 --> 00:14:37.830 align:middle line:84%
And I got the old
punch and hammer again.

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:38.630 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Uh-huh.

00:14:38.630 --> 00:14:40.390 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Can't
make a mark on it.

00:14:40.390 --> 00:14:45.490 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going, God almighty,
who's working this stuff?

00:14:45.490 --> 00:14:49.450 align:middle line:10%
So anyway, all the parts
came back in, hooked it all

00:14:49.450 --> 00:14:53.870 align:middle line:10%
together, Pitholem was born.

00:14:53.870 --> 00:14:57.070 align:middle line:10%
That was June 20, 1971.

00:14:57.070 --> 00:14:59.650 align:middle line:10%
But to get to this point
I'm telling you about,

00:14:59.650 --> 00:15:05.638 align:middle line:10%
26 and a half months, seven
days a week, 14, 16 hours a day.

00:15:05.638 --> 00:15:07.180 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY: You used
all six tons of it?

00:15:07.180 --> 00:15:08.020 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: All of it.

00:15:08.020 --> 00:15:09.430 align:middle line:90%
There's no more of this.

00:15:09.430 --> 00:15:14.560 align:middle line:10%
So one half of phase
one is where we're at.

00:15:14.560 --> 00:15:17.230 align:middle line:84%
I want to go all the
way to phase four,

00:15:17.230 --> 00:15:21.160 align:middle line:84%
but come to find out, they
stop at one half of phase one.

00:15:21.160 --> 00:15:27.260 align:middle line:84%
They got what they wanted,
a speed vehicle in like--

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:29.030 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: What kind of cargo?

00:15:29.030 --> 00:15:30.890 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Well, that
was to be determined.

00:15:30.890 --> 00:15:32.432 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know what
they wanted to do.

00:15:32.432 --> 00:15:35.000 align:middle line:84%
But come to find out
later, they wanted

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.850 align:middle line:84%
to put a thermonuclear
warhead on it

00:15:37.850 --> 00:15:40.260 align:middle line:90%
and aim it at the Soviet Union.

00:15:40.260 --> 00:15:42.350 align:middle line:84%
But there's more designs
to the whole thing.

00:15:42.350 --> 00:15:44.480 align:middle line:84%
It's a bigger
program than just me.

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:47.000 align:middle line:90%
I'm part of the program.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.830 align:middle line:10%
The whole program was--

00:15:49.830 --> 00:15:54.720 align:middle line:10%
you've got to know General
LeMay, chief of the Joint

00:15:54.720 --> 00:16:00.180 align:middle line:10%
Chiefs, nicknamed Bombs Away
LeMay, bombed the living

00:16:00.180 --> 00:16:03.870 align:middle line:10%
daylights out of everything that
was living in World War II, one

00:16:03.870 --> 00:16:08.010 align:middle line:10%
of the principal people
responsible for our success

00:16:08.010 --> 00:16:09.660 align:middle line:10%
in World War II.

00:16:09.660 --> 00:16:12.210 align:middle line:84%
He became the chief
of the Joint Chiefs,

00:16:12.210 --> 00:16:16.890 align:middle line:84%
designer of the B-52
Stratofortress, founder of SAC,

00:16:16.890 --> 00:16:19.150 align:middle line:84%
Strategic Air Command,
our nuclear defense force.

00:16:19.150 --> 00:16:19.950 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Massive.

00:16:19.950 --> 00:16:28.950 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Guy's got
massive oomph with him.

00:16:28.950 --> 00:16:36.400 align:middle line:10%
And he's the one that said
in history, to the North

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:39.130 align:middle line:10%
Vietnamese, if you don't come
to the Paris peace talks,

00:16:39.130 --> 00:16:41.830 align:middle line:10%
I'm going to bomb you
back into the Stone Age.

00:16:41.830 --> 00:16:44.800 align:middle line:84%
That's who said
it, General LeMay.

00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:49.660 align:middle line:84%
Next day, he's fired by
Secretary of Defense Robert

00:16:49.660 --> 00:16:51.370 align:middle line:90%
McNamara.

00:16:51.370 --> 00:16:52.960 align:middle line:90%
Did that slow him down?

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:55.620 align:middle line:84%
No, it was like stepping
on the accelerator

00:16:55.620 --> 00:16:58.420 align:middle line:84%
because, if you just
look a pictures of him,

00:16:58.420 --> 00:17:01.080 align:middle line:90%
he's not going to be fired.

00:17:01.080 --> 00:17:06.300 align:middle line:10%
So he's got designs,
and what he wanted was--

00:17:06.300 --> 00:17:10.210 align:middle line:10%
he wants the B-52s
retired, replaced

00:17:10.210 --> 00:17:17.150 align:middle line:10%
by 45 XB-70s called a Valkyrie.

00:17:17.150 --> 00:17:20.930 align:middle line:10%
This Valkyrie thing
you had to see.

00:17:20.930 --> 00:17:24.550 align:middle line:10%
It's a delta wing bomber.

00:17:24.550 --> 00:17:27.660 align:middle line:90%
The delta wing is gigantic.

00:17:27.660 --> 00:17:29.980 align:middle line:90%
It'd fill a football field.

00:17:29.980 --> 00:17:33.390 align:middle line:84%
People walk on it and they
look like specks on this thing.

00:17:33.390 --> 00:17:36.270 align:middle line:84%
So they wanted to
take the Valkyrie,

00:17:36.270 --> 00:17:39.615 align:middle line:84%
take Pitholem, shove a couple
Pitholems into Valkyrie.

00:17:39.615 --> 00:17:40.663 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Oh, goodness.

00:17:40.663 --> 00:17:42.330 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: You come in
2,000 miles an hour

00:17:42.330 --> 00:17:47.590 align:middle line:84%
to fail-safe, to the Soviet
radar net, open up the bomb

00:17:47.590 --> 00:17:48.390 align:middle line:90%
bay doors.

00:17:48.390 --> 00:17:53.990 align:middle line:84%
And just as you're penetrating
fail-safe, drop Pitholem out.

00:17:53.990 --> 00:17:57.330 align:middle line:84%
Here she goes into
ludicrous speed.

00:17:57.330 --> 00:17:59.970 align:middle line:84%
The Soviets will look on
the scopes and see a streak

00:17:59.970 --> 00:18:01.800 align:middle line:90%
and go, what's that?

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:04.363 align:middle line:84%
And by the time they say,
what's, they're dust.

00:18:04.363 --> 00:18:05.280 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: They're gone.

00:18:05.280 --> 00:18:07.050 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: They're gone.

00:18:07.050 --> 00:18:12.120 align:middle line:84%
So they win MAD, mutual
assured destruction,

00:18:12.120 --> 00:18:14.300 align:middle line:90%
a program we live under today.

00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:17.330 align:middle line:84%
And it goes that, you're
America, I'm Soviet Union.

00:18:17.330 --> 00:18:19.130 align:middle line:84%
If we attack each
other, you can be

00:18:19.130 --> 00:18:22.010 align:middle line:84%
mutually assured we're
going to kill each other,

00:18:22.010 --> 00:18:24.450 align:middle line:90%
and we don't fight.

00:18:24.450 --> 00:18:27.915 align:middle line:84%
However, if you've got
first strike capability,

00:18:27.915 --> 00:18:33.737 align:middle line:84%
it means I hit you so fast
you can't retaliate, I win.

00:18:33.737 --> 00:18:34.945 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: This is about speed.

00:18:34.945 --> 00:18:36.653 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: I'm pulled
into all this stuff.

00:18:36.653 --> 00:18:37.570 align:middle line:90%
>>EMERY: Oh, goodness.

00:18:37.570 --> 00:18:39.778 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: And they didn't
tell me anything about this.

00:18:39.778 --> 00:18:42.263 align:middle line:84%
I'm learning it, finding
out as we're going--

00:18:42.263 --> 00:18:44.430 align:middle line:84%
>>EMERY: So basically,
you're telling me the fastest

00:18:44.430 --> 00:18:47.490 align:middle line:90%
person to kill the planet wins.

00:18:47.490 --> 00:18:48.840 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Exactly.

00:18:48.840 --> 00:18:51.467 align:middle line:10%
So the whole thing was
just what it was, mad.

00:18:51.467 --> 00:18:52.800 align:middle line:10%
>>EMERY: This is how they think.

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:54.270 align:middle line:10%
>>ADAIR: Crazy.

00:18:54.270 --> 00:18:57.510 align:middle line:10%
And they were so
focused on one thing,

00:18:57.510 --> 00:19:01.420 align:middle line:10%
